# Git Conventions

## Commit Format — Conventional Commits

```
<type>(<scope>): <short description>

[optional body]
```

Types:
- `feat` — new feature
- `fix` — bug fix
- `refactor` — code change with no feature/fix
- `test` — adding or updating tests
- `docs` — documentation only
- `chore` — tooling, deps, config

Examples:
```
feat(search): add semantic reranking to query pipeline
fix(agents): handle LLM timeout with retry backoff
refactor(search): extract query builder to separate class
test(search): add integration tests for opensearch repository
docs: add ADR for modular monolith decision
chore: upgrade opensearch-py to 2.7
```

## Branch Naming

```
feat/<short-slug>      # feat/semantic-reranking
fix/<short-slug>       # fix/llm-timeout
chore/<short-slug>     # chore/upgrade-opensearch
```

## Commit Hygiene

- One logical change per commit — no "fix everything" commits
- pre-commit hooks enforce automatically on every `git commit`:
  1. `ruff check --fix` — lint
  2. `ruff format` — formatting
  3. `pytest tests/unit/ -q` — unit tests must pass
  4. commit-msg check — forbidden AI tool names

To install hooks after cloning:
```powershell
uv run pre-commit install
```

## Commit Message — Forbidden Words

**Never mention AI tool or model names** in commit messages.
Write "agent" when referring to AI-assisted work.

```
# ❌ FORBIDDEN in commit messages:
# Cursor, Claude, ChatGPT, GPT-4, Copilot, OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, Mistral

# ✅ CORRECT — generic "agent"
refactor(search): fix module boundary violation found by agent
docs: update rules based on agent audit recommendations
```

The `no-ai-tool-names` pre-commit hook will reject commits containing these words.

## Never Commit

- `.env` files (real credentials)
- `uv.lock` changes without corresponding `pyproject.toml` dependency changes
- Generated files or build artifacts
- `.cursor/rules/local/*.mdc` (personal developer profiles)
